    diagnosticCriteria: 'Diagnosis is clinical based on history of brief positional vertigo and positive Dix-Hallpike maneuver. Nystagmus observed during testing confirms the diagnosis and involved canal. Audiometry is normal. MRI brain is not required unless atypical features present.',
    firstLineTreatment: 'Canalith repositioning maneuvers (Epley maneuver for posterior canal, Semont maneuver, Barbecue roll for horizontal canal). Vestibular suppressants (betahistine, prochlorperazine) for acute nausea only. Vestibular rehabilitation exercises (Brandt-Daroff) for refractory cases.',
    complications: ["Falls and injuries during vertigo episodes", "Recurrence (approximately 50% within 5 years)", "Residual dizziness after successful treatment", "Anxiety about future episodes", "Rare: failure to resolve requiring surgical intervention (canal plugging)"],
    prognosis: 'Excellent - most cases resolve spontaneously within weeks. Canalith repositioning achieves 80-90% success rate. Recurrence is common (up to 50% within 5 years) but repeat treatment is effective.',
    prevention: ["Avoid sudden head movements during active episodes", "Sleep with head elevated on 2 pillows", "Avoid rapid head turning", "Vestibular exercises to promote compensation"],
    patientEducation: ["BPPV is caused by loose crystals in the inner ear - not a stroke or brain problem", "The Epley maneuver is highly effective and can be done in clinic", "You may need 1-3 treatment sessions for complete resolution", "Return if vertigo is continuous (not just positional) or accompanied by hearing loss or neurological symptoms"],
    references: ["American Academy of Otolaryngology Clinical Practice Guideline: BPPV", "Barany Society Diagnostic Criteria for BPPV"],
