    overview: 'Pregnancy is the physiological state of a developing embryo/fetus within the uterus, typically lasting 40 weeks (280 days) from the last menstrual period. It involves profound anatomical, physiological, and hormonal changes across all organ systems to support fetal growth and prepare for childbirth.',
    epidemiology: 'Approximately 140 million pregnancies occur annually worldwide. 85% of women giving birth have at least one pregnancy in their lifetime. Maternal mortality ratio is 211 per 100,000 live births globally (2017), with wide variation between high and low-income countries.',
    riskFactors: ["Advanced maternal age (≥35 years)", "Multiple gestation (twins, triplets)", "Pre-existing medical conditions (diabetes, hypertension, thyroid disease)", "Previous pregnancy complications (pre-eclampsia, preterm birth, miscarriage)", "Obesity (BMI ≥30)", "Smoking, alcohol, or substance use during pregnancy", "Poor prenatal care", "Low socioeconomic status"],
    typicalPresentation: ["Missed period (amenorrhea) - most common presenting symptom", "Nausea and vomiting (\'morning sickness\') - typically weeks 6-12", "Breast tenderness and enlargement", "Fatigue and increased sleep requirement", "Urinary frequency", "Food cravings or aversions", "Mood swings and emotional lability", "Positive home pregnancy test"],
    clinicalSigns: ["Positive urine or serum hCG pregnancy test", "Enlarged, soft uterus on bimanual examination", "Hegar sign (softening of the lower uterine segment)", "Chadwick sign (bluish discoloration of cervix and vagina)", "Goodell sign (softening of the cervix)", "Breast changes: darkened areolae, Montgomery tubercles", "Fetal heart tones detectable by Doppler (10-12 weeks)", "Fetal movements palpable (18-22 weeks in primigravida, 16-18 in multigravida)"],
    diagnosticCriteria: 'Positive urine hCG (sensitive at 12-14 days after conception). Serum β-hCG: ≥25 mIU/mL confirms pregnancy. Transvaginal ultrasound: gestational sac visible at 4.5-5 weeks, fetal pole and cardiac activity at 5.5-6 weeks. Transabdominal ultrasound: visible at 6-7 weeks. Dating ultrasound (crown-rump length) at 10-13 weeks is most accurate for gestational age.',
    firstLineTreatment: 'Prenatal care with regular antenatal visits. Folic acid 400-800 mcg daily (preconception through first 12 weeks) for neural tube defect prevention. Iron supplementation if anemic. Prenatal vitamins. Screening: aneuploidy screening (first trimester combined screen, NIPT), anatomy scan at 18-22 weeks, GDM screening at 24-28 weeks. Group B Streptococcus screening at 35-37 weeks.',
    complications: ["Miscarriage (15-20% of recognized pregnancies)", "Ectopic pregnancy (1-2%)", "Pre-eclampsia (5-8%) and eclampsia", "Gestational diabetes (6-9%)", "Preterm birth (<37 weeks, 10%)", "Postpartum hemorrhage"],
    prognosis: 'Most pregnancies (85-90%) result in a healthy term live birth. Maternal mortality in high-income countries is very low (10-20 per 100,000). In low-income countries, maternal mortality remains high (500-1000 per 100,000). Fetal outcomes depend on prenatal care, maternal health, and access to obstetric services.',
    prevention: ["Preconception counseling and optimization of maternal health", "Folic acid supplementation before and during early pregnancy", "Avoid alcohol, tobacco, and recreational drugs", "Maintain healthy diet and appropriate weight gain", "Regular prenatal care attendance", "Manage chronic medical conditions before and during pregnancy", "Vaccination: influenza, Tdap, COVID-19"],
    patientEducation: ["Take prenatal vitamins with folic acid daily", "Attend all scheduled prenatal appointments", "Seek immediate care for: vaginal bleeding, severe abdominal pain, severe headache, vision changes, reduced fetal movements", "Morning sickness is normal but severe vomiting needs treatment", "Most medications need review during pregnancy - don\'t stop essential medications without consulting your doctor", "Breastfeeding is recommended for the first 6 months"],
    references: ["ACOG Clinical Guidelines for Obstetric Care", "NICE Guidelines on Antenatal Care", "WHO Recommendations on Antenatal Care"],
